Brasil Foods, Lan, PDG, Petrobras: Latin America Equity Preview

-- B y   K a t i a   P o r z e c a n s k i
-- 
2011-10-04T05:51:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-04/brasil-foods-lan-pdg-petrobras-latin-america-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  The MSCI  Latin America  Index fell 3.6 percent to 3,220.56.  Brazil  BRF - Brasil Foods SA (BRFS3)  (BRFS3 BS): The world’s largest
poultry exporter said its subsidiary in  Argentina  acquired
control of Empresa Avex SA to boost distribution of dried goods
and refrigerated products. The acquisition includes total
investments of about $150 million, Brasil Foods said in a
regulatory filing. The shares slid 2.3 percent to 31.45 reais.  Gol Linhas Aereas Inteligentes SA (GOLL4 BS): Brazil’s
second-largest airline by market share said it paid 70 million
reais ($37 million) to acquire control of Webjet Linhas Aereas
SA, according to a regulatory filing. The stock slumped 5.6
percent to 9.67 reais.  PDG Realty SA Empreendimentos & Participacoes (PDGR3 BS):
 Brazil ’s biggest homebuilder by revenue reported contracted
sales of 1.91 billion reais in the third quarter, up 3.3 percent
from a year earlier. The stock dropped 4.4 percent to 5.86
reais.        Petroleo Brasileiro SA (PETR4)  (PETR4 BS): Brazil’s state-
controlled oil company said a subsidiary reached an agreement to
“farm out” 50 percent of two blocks in Tanzania to Shell
Deepwater Tanzania BV. Separately, the Rio de Janeiro-based
company said in an e-mailed statement it received bids for 21
drillships that will be built in Brazil and used in deep waters.
Petrobras will continue as the blocks’ operator. The shares fell
3.6 percent to 18.41 reais.  Chile   Lan Airlines SA (LAN)  : Pal Airlines filed a claim in
Chile’s  Supreme Court  to block its rival, Lan, from taking over
Brazil’s Tam SA, a transaction that would create the world’s
second-largest airline by market value, Pal said in a an e-
mailed statement. Shares of Latin America’s largest carrier by
market value dropped 4.3 percent to 10,529 pesos.  Colombia   Exporters: United States President  Barack Obama  sent
pending free-trade agreements with Colombia to Congress
yesterday after lawmakers created a path for renewing benefits
for workers who lose their jobs to foreign competition.  Coltejer SA (COLTEJ)  , a Colombian clothing maker and
exporter, fell 4.6 percent to 1.04 pesos.  Enka de Colombia SA (ENKA) 
, a Medellin-based synthetic fibers producer, climbed
2.9 percent to 10.60 pesos. Fabricato SA (FABRI CB), Colombia’s
biggest textile maker, gained 0.7 percent to 72.00 pesos.  To contact the reporters on this story:
